1. d4 f5 {"A risky defence which up to the present I have adopted only very
infrequently in serious games.   But in the prsent game I had positively to
play for a win in order to make sure of first prize, whereas a draw was
sufficient for my opponent to secure third prize, and hence I found myself
forced to run some risks." - Alekhine} 2. c4 {According to Alekhine, it is
better fo begin with 2 g3, so that Black should not be able to exchange his
f8-bishop. But is this really to his advantage?} Nf6 3. g3 e6 4. Bg2 Bb4+ 5.
Bd2 {[pgndiagram]} (5. Nd2 {And now correct is} O-O $1 ({But not} 5... Ne4 $2
6. a3 Nxd2 7. Bxd2 Bxd2+ 8. Qxd2 O-O 9. Nh3 d5 10. cxd5 exd5 11. Nf4 c6 12. O-O
Qe7 13. b4 $1 {With clear advantage, Alekhine - Tartakower, San Remo 1930}))
5... Bxd2+ 6. Nxd2 (6. Qxd2 {Is the main move in my database} O-O 7. Nc3 {And
White's knight is more active on c3}) 6... Nc6 7. Ngf3 O-O 8. O-O {[pgndiagram]
} (8. Qc2 {Was Tartakower idea, with the intention of e4. But I think that
Black counter this idea efficiently with e6-e5} d6 9. e4 Nxe4 10. Nxe4 Nb4 $1 {
Important intermediate move} (10... fxe4 11. Qxe4 e5 12. dxe5 Bf5 13. Qd5+ Kh8)
11. Qe2 fxe4 12. Qxe4 e5 13. dxe5 Bf5 {[pgndiagram] Now wins immediately}) 8...
d6 9. Qb3 Kh8 $2 {Not a necessary move} (9... e5 {Was imemdiately possible} 10.
c5+ Kh8 11. d5 Ne7 12. cxd6 cxd6 13. Ng5 e4 {And Black has nothing to fear})
10. Qc3 $2 {"It is already difficult to suggest a satisfactory line of play
for White" - Alekhine. But he underestimated the advance of the d pawn} (10. d5
$1 {Preventing e6-e5 or forcing a weakening would have been incredibly strong}
Na5 (10... exd5 11. cxd5 Ne7 12. Nd4 Bd7 13. Rac1 {And White is better}) 11.
Qa3 c5 12. dxc6 Nxc6 13. Rad1 {And Black's d6 pawn means he will be on
defensive}) 10... e5 $1 {[pgndiagram] Now Black has equalized and can face the
future with optimism} 11. e3 (11. dxe5 dxe5 {Is the alternative} 12. e4 $1 {A
direct equalizer} (12. Rad1 {Is the only move mentioned by Kasparov, but after}
Qe7 13. Rfe1 e4 {Black has reasonable chances of seizing the initiative}) 12...
fxe4 13. Ng5 Bg4 14. Rae1 (14. Ngxe4 Nd4 15. Kh1 {And Black is slightly better}
) 14... Nd4 15. f3 Nxf3+ 16. Ndxf3 exf3 17. Nxf3 Bxf3 18. Bxf3 e4 19. Bxe4 Nxe4
20. Rxf8+ Qxf8 21. Rxe4 {[pgndiagram] And this long computer line results in
dead equal endgame}) 11... a5 $1 {Grabbing some space and hindering future b4}
12. b3 Qe8 13. a3 (13. d5 {Perhaps White should decide on this move, in order
not to allow Black to carry out this advance}) 13... Qh5 {[pgndiagram] "A
start of a deep strategic plan. First of all Black creates threats on the
kingside and provokes a weakening of the opponent's pawns." - Kotov} (13... e4
{Was possibly stronger nevertheless} 14. Ne1 d5 $1) 14. h4 {Threatening dxe5} (
14. dxe5 dxe5 15. Nxe5 $4 Nxe5 16. Qxe5 Ng4 {Just loses}) 14... Ng4 (14... e4
$5) 15. Ng5 $1 {A good move, removing the knight from potential attack and
bringing it to h3 to bolster the f4 square} (15. b4 axb4 16. axb4 Rxa1 17. Rxa1
f4 $5 {Is slightly unpleasant for White}) 15... Bd7 (15... h6 16. Nh3) 16. f3
$2 {[pgndiagram] But this is a serious mistake, weakening the kingside} (16. b4
{Was preferable} axb4 17. axb4 Rxa1 18. Rxa1 f4 19. exf4 exf4 20. Nh3 $1 {The
point behind Ng5} fxg3 21. fxg3 Ne7 22. Nf4 {[pgndiagram] And White remains in
control}) 16... Nf6 17. f4 {Now this is practically forced} (17. b4 exd4 18.
exd4 f4 {Leads to a fearfully strong attack} 19. gxf4 Qxh4) 17... e4 {From
this moment onwards, Black is firmly in control} 18. Rfd1 (18. d5 {Was
suggested, preventing Black from advancing in the centre, but I am not certain
that it helps him all that much.}) 18... h6 19. Nh3 d5 $5 {[pgndiagram] This
advance was praised many times, but the alternatives are also attractive,
since White's light squares are fatally weak :)} (19... a4 20. b4 b5 $1) (19...
Ne7 20. Nf2 a4) 20. Nf1 Ne7 21. a4 $6 {Once again I am not sure whether this
was required} Nc6 22. Rd2 Nb4 23. Bh1 {With the hope of playing Rg2-Nf2 and g4
in the future} Qe8 $1 {Practically winning the a4 pawn} 24. Rg2 dxc4 25. bxc4 {
[pgndiagram] Bogoljubow decides to give up a pawn} (25. Qxc4 b5 {IS no better})
25... Bxa4 26. Nf2 Bd7 27. Nd2 (27. g4 {Doesn't really work} fxg4 28. Ng3 b5)
27... b5 $1 {Fighting for the d5 square} 28. Nd1 Nd3 $1 {A prelude to one of
the most remarkable combinations in the history of chess} 29. Rxa5 {Bogoljubow
misses the point, but it is hard to blame him for that, honestly} b4 $3 {
[pgndiagram] One of those remarkable Alekhine combinations that a chess player
remembers for his whole life} (29... Qh5 {Would lead to a more prosaic win} 30.
Nf2 Qe2 31. Nxd3 Qxe3+ 32. Kh2 Ng4+) 30. Rxa8 bxc3 $3 31. Rxe8 c2 $3 {
[pgndiagram] The point of the combination. White can't prevent this pawn from
queening} 32. Rxf8+ Kh7 33. Nf2 c1=Q+ {White's rook has captured three Black's
major pieces, but the mere pawn has proved to be more valuable. For the moment
White has material equality, but his pieces and numerous weaknesses are a
sorry sight.} 34. Nf1 Ne1 35. Rh2 Qxc4 {[pgndiagram] The rest doesn't require
serious commentary} 36. Rb8 Bb5 37. Rxb5 {There is nothing else} Qxb5 38. g4
Nf3+ 39. Bxf3 exf3 40. gxf5 Qe2 41. d5 Kg8 42. h5 Kh7 43. e4 Nxe4 44. Nxe4 Qxe4
45. d6 cxd6 46. f6 gxf6 47. Rd2 Qe2 $1 {[pgndiagram] A very nice final touch,
worthy of this game.} 48. Rxe2 {Forced, due to the threat of mate on g2} fxe2 {
For the second time in this game, we see the strength of a pawn on the second
rank over the knight} 49. Kf2 exf1=Q+ 50. Kxf1 Kg7 {And the pawn endgame is
easily won for Black.} 51. Ke2 Kf7 52. Ke3 Ke6 53. Ke4 d5+ {One of the best
games in the history of chess and without a doubt my favourite Alehkine game.
Simply brilliant} 0-1

