1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 Bb4 5. e5 h6 6. exf6 {[pgndiagram] I think
that nowadays this move is not that much in vogue, although probably it is
better than it looks} (6. Bd2 {Is the main line}) (6. Be3 {Is also fairly
common in my database}) 6... hxg5 7. fxg7 Rg8 8. h4 {[pgndiagram] Surprisingly,
this is all theory.} (8. a3 {Has also appeared. This position is worth
examining more closely} Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 Rxg7 10. Qh5 Rg8 11. Qh7 Kf8 12. h4 {
When White has decend chances of seizing the initiative, in my view}) 8... gxh4
9. Qg4 {An attempt to improve on the variation with Qh5 - Kasparov} (9. Qh5 Qf6
10. Nf3 Nc6 (10... Qxg7 {Is simpler}) 11. Rxh4 (11. Qxh4 {Is probably the
safest}) 11... Qxg7 12. O-O-O Bd7 {When Black already has a preferable position
}) 9... Be7 $6 {I don't like this reply} (9... Qf6 {Seems simpler, immediately
