1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 {Flohr was famous for his technical style and Queen's
Gambit Accepted is fully in accordance with it} 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 {It is
strange to see Alekhine choosing the quiet 3 Nf3 4 e3 continuation} e6 5. Bxc4
c5 6. O-O Nc6 7. Qe2 a6 8. Rd1 $3 {[pgndiagram] The exclamation marks are not
for the quality of the move, but for the breakthrough in time. Alekhine
realizes that he can do without a4 and immediately develops a piece} (8. a4 {
Was played almost exclusively, but this gave Black the b4 square and I don't
think that White has all that much in that variation. White players
subsequently tried other paths, but for 1931 move such as 8 Rd1 was a
revelation}) 8... b5 9. dxc5 Qc7 10. Bd3 Bxc5 11. a4 $1 {[pgndiagram] The
point! In many modern openings, White induces Black to advance his pawn to b5,
in order to be able to undermine it with a4} b4 (11... bxa4 {Is ugly, but
might be better nevertheless, reducing the number of the pawns on the queenside
}) 12. Nbd2 (12. b3 $5 {With development of the bishop on b2, was worth
considering. But Alekhine occupies the square with the knight instead}) 12...
O-O 13. Nb3 Be7 14. e4 $1 {[pgndiagram] A correct move, advancing in the
center and  increasing the scope of the dark squared bishop} Nd7 {Anticipating
the e5 advance, but it was better to complete the development} (14... Bb7 15.
e5 Nd7 16. Bf4 {Although even here Black's position is unpleasant, at least
his rooks are connected and all his pieces are developed}) 15. Be3 Nde5 $6 {
Once again moving the knight. In general, it is a good idea for the side with
less space to exchange pieces, but here this is too slow} (15... Bb7 16. Rac1 {
Would lead to a position similar to the one examined in the previous note}) 16.
Nxe5 Nxe5 17. Rac1 Qb8 18. Bc5 $1 {[pgndiagram] A great decision, exchanging 
Black's better bishop in order to establish a knight on c5, which will
dominate the bishop on c8} Bxc5 19. Nxc5 Qb6 20. Qh5 Nd7 21. Be2 $6 {Probably
it was stronger not to allow a knight exchange} (21. Nb3 {Came into
consideration here}) 21... g6 {Before exchanging, Black creates "luft" for his
king, which is always useful} 22. Qg5 Nxc5 23. Rxc5 a5 24. h4 {[pgndiagram]
Despite White's slight inaccuracy on move 21, he still has a dominant position
(control of the open files, better minor piece, more space, chances of attack)}
Ba6 25. Bf3 f6 {Fearing the threat of h5-h6, Flohr weakens his king. It was
probably wiser not to move the pawns} (25... Rad8 26. Rdc1 Rc8 27. h5 Qd8 28.
Qe3 {And Black has some chances of resisting, although White retains a large
portion of his advantage}) 26. Qe3 {[pgndiagram] Now Black's difficulties
increase further} Rad8 27. Rxd8 Rxd8 $2 {Losing immediately} (27... Qxd8 {Was
more resilient, but as it is..}) 28. e5 $1 {The consequence of 25... f6. White
also takes away the d6 square from the Black Queen} (28. Rc8 Qd6 {Is probably
also winning, though}) 28... f5 $2 {But this loses immediately} (28... Kf7 {Is
the best move according to the engine, but this tells everything about Black's
position} 29. exf6) 29. Rc8 {[pgndiagram] Black loses a full rook, or a queen
for rook. Therefore he resigned. A beautiful positional win in the style of
Capablanca.} 1-0

